leader, she said, who is unique in his
time.

“Even after being released from
jail, he fought for the liberation of
blacks. Now that he has been elected,
he wants to build a new vision of a
united South Africa. Right now we
are in that transition,” said Mandela.
“And we believe whether or not we
succeed depends on South Africans
—— both black and white.”

But Mandela also cautioned that
while her father is key to the transi-
tion, he alone cannot be the solution.

“Many believe that Nelson Mandela
has miraculous powers,” she said.
“But 350 years of oppression cannot
be wiped out overnight. And it can-
not be the work of one man.”

She also believes that it is impor-
tant for South Africans to continue to

be honest with themselves and with
outsiders, realizing that the road to
equality will be long and difficult.
She said they must admit they’re
struggling and that the journey is far
from over.

“The legacy of the past is with us.
and it has deep roots,” said Mandela,
who received both her master’s and
doctorate degrees at the University of
Massachusetts. “We know we have
come a long way, but we, also realize
our transition is not complete. I think
we have made great strides, but the
ending of the apartheid regime is not
an end to racism and prejudice _——- it
