Be all you can be

One United States Circuit Court apparently neglected to read the
Constitution last week, since it decided (9-4) that the military’s homo-
sexual “don’t ask, don’t tell” policy was valid.

Instead of basing its employment policies on capability or even, just
maybe, quality of performance, the military has deemed that certain
people (based on lifestyles not effecting their careers) are not suitable
to serve their country. This is utterly ridiculous.

There used to be a time when women were not allowed to serve in
the military; they still aren’t allowed in some military job categories.
Blacks weren’t allowed to serve in desegregated units until fairly recent
wars. Discrimination against those groups has been (mostly) eliminat-
ed in military enlistment. But discrimination against homosexuals in
the military is a time-honored tradition, and this time the courts are
backing it.

Whether you believe that homosexuality is a biologically determined
fact or a personal choice doesn’t really matter. Either way, a person is
still homosexual; and either way, there is no physical defect which
automatically prevents faithful and effective service in the military.

President Clinton’s much-lauded “don’t ask, don’t tell” policy,
though a step in the right direction, still leaves room for any homosexu-
al to be kicked out of the military. Whether that person blatantly states
his or her homosexuality or accidentally slips “out of the closet” for a
second shouldn’t matter either. The military, by requiring homosexuals
to maintain secrecy, has committed a gross violation of the freedom of
speech. If a person wants to stand on top of a hillside and armounce
his/her homosexuality, it shouldn’t matter, so long as the armounce-
ment does not take place when that person is supposed to be on duty.

“Don’t ask, don’t tell’’ is based on the premise that some people
would be uncomfortable serving in a unit with a homosexual. The
question is, who’s problem is that? Of course, the rnilitary’s purpose is
not to instruct its soldiers in sensitivity or political rhetoric. But if a sol-
dier has a problem serving next to a homosexual, it’s that soldier’s
problem. If there were a confrontation or assault against a gay soldier,
legal action should be taken in a court-marshal.

Homosexuals have been serving in the military for hundreds of
years, at times holding very high-ranking oﬂices. If youare in the mili-
tary now, there-is a strong possibility that one of the people in your unit
is gay — you might never know. But if that person is performing his or
her job well, it shouldn’t make a difference.

If you found out ‘tomorrow that soldier X (who is well-decorated for
meritorious service) was gay, that fact wouldn’t change X’s past
record. And if you develop a personal hatred for X, it is only based on
your own ignorance. X would still do the same job he or she had done
in the past V

As long as a soldier can effectively do the job he or she was hired to
do, it should not matter if that soldier is gay, lesbian, straight, androgy-
nous or anything else. I

