Mullins sprints to track
stardom after a slow start baseball games

By Geoff Moak
Staff Writer

“Tonya Mullins is independent, a
strong woman, attractive, intelligent, per-
sonable. And talented.”

Those words of praise for the Pitt
senior and track star come from Head
Coach Steve Lewis. Even though Lewis
added “talented” almost as an after-
thought, it is hardly the least of Mullins’
traits.

Mullins has the eighth fastest time in
Pitt history in the 100-meter hurdles,
14.23 seconds, and in her junior year, she
was part of the Pitt indoor shuttle hurdle
relay team that set a world record of
29.10 seconds.

This year, at the Alabama Relays in
mid—March, Mullins was a part of Pitt’s
mile relay, the shuttle hurdle relay, and
the 800-meter relay. Plus, she competed
in the heptathlon — seven events in two
days. All in one weekend.

More importantly, she did them all
well. The first two of her three relay
teams won, and the 800-meter relay team
was winning before an ofﬁcial’s mistake
took the lead away. In the heptathlon, she
qualified for the ECAC championships.

Success is not new to Mullins. As a
sophomore in high school, she was ninth
in the nation at 400 meters and had one
of the top 10 300-meter times ever
recorded by a female high school athlete.
Not too shabby for someone who didn’t
even start running until eighth grade.

“My P.E. teacher said to me, ‘Won’t
you come out for the track team? You
could be really good, and it can take you
places.’ So I came out one day,” Mullins
said.

Track certainly has taken her places.
It’s taken her (and her teammates) to
Nebraska, Alabama, even Jamaica —
and that’s just in the past two months. It
can be a taxing schedule, but Mullins
came to college prepared for the travel.

Mullins was born in South Carolina
but grew up and had gone to high school
in Virginia. Her father was in the mili-
tary, so her family was displaced several
times. In Mullins’ junior year of high
school, her father was reassigned, and
her close-knit family moved to Copperas
Cove, Texas, where Mullins graduated
from high school.

Such moving may have brought her
closer to her family (so close that she
even refers to her cousins as “brothers
and sisters”), and it may have helped pre-
pare Mullins for the college travel sched-
ule, but on at least one occasion, it hurt
her athletics. The move from Virginia to
Texas brought her track career tumbling
down even faster than she had built it,
sending Mullins into a brief period of
uncharacteristic apathy.

“I didn’t run track. I played soccer and
volleyball and ran cross country. I got
uprooted, and at the time, my heart
wasn’t in it, so I didn’t do a lot,” Mullins
said.

